'''Andrew Ian McNamara''' (born 19 August 1959) is an [[Australia]]n politician. He was a [[Australian Labor Party (Queensland Branch)|Labor]] member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Queensland]] from 2001 to 2009, representing the district of [[Electoral district of Hervey Bay|Hervey Bay]]. He served as Minister for Sustainability, Climate Change and Innovation from 2007 to 2009, under the premiership of [[Anna Bligh]]. Currently, Mr McNamara was the CEO of the [[Chiropractors' Association of Australia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/chiropractic-fraternity-splits-over-allegations-of-mismanagement-20150708-gi7qxd.html|title=Chiropractic fraternity splits over allegations of mismanagement|last=|first=|date=11 July 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=|access-date=14 January 2017}}</ref>

==Peak oil==

In February 2005, McNamara came to national prominence as the first mainstream Australian politician to speak out on the issue of [[Peak Oil]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/National/Running-on-empty/2005/04/01/1112302233942.html|title=Running On Empty|date=2 April 2005|publisher=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.globalpublicmedia.com/lectures/360|title=Australian Politician Goes on record about Peak Oil and Gas|date=22 February 2005|publisher=Global Public Media|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050309102033/http://www.globalpublicmedia.com/lectures/360|archivedate=9 March 2005|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

McNamara was the Chair of the Queensland Government's Oil Vulnerability Taskforce.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/items/200505/1373249.htm?widebay|title=New task force to tackle oil woes|date=20 May 2005|publisher=ABC}}</ref> The Taskforce report, "Queensland's Vulnerability to Rising Oil Prices," also known as the [[McNamara Report]] was commissioned in 2005 and is the first of its kind to be commissioned by any government in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://globalpublicmedia.com/new_queensland_sustainability_minister_on_the_future_with_less_oil|title=New Queensland Sustainability Minister on the future with less oil|date=19 September 2007|publisher=Global Public Media|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011214724/http://globalpublicmedia.com/new_queensland_sustainability_minister_on_the_future_with_less_oil|archivedate=11 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> McNamara is also the Foundation Patron of the Australian Association  for the Study of Peak Oil (ASPO).

==Climate change==
Andrew McNamara was a member of Australia's delegation to the Bali Climate Change Conference in December 2007. McNamara has also established a Climate Change Council with a number of prominent environmentalists and business leaders including [[Tim Flannery]] and [[Ian Lowe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://statements.qld.gov.au/Statement/Id/55615|title=Media Statements|last=|first=|date=December 11, 2007|website=Queensland  Cabinet and Ministerial Directory|publisher=[[Queensland Government]]|access-date=14 January 2017}}</ref>

==Anti-whaling==
Andrew McNamara has been a strong opponent of [[whaling]], particularly Japanese whaling in Australian waters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2008-02-20/mcnamara-to-send-anti-whaling-message-to-japan/1048192|title=McNamara to send anti-whaling message to Japan|last=|first=|date=20 February 2008|website=ABC News|publisher=ABC|access-date=14 January 2017}}</ref>

==Hervey Bay==
Andrew McNamara represented the seat of [[Electoral district of Hervey Bay|Hervey Bay]].  [[Hervey Bay]] is one of the fastest growing areas in [[Australia]].  The area's principal industry is tourism, in particular whale watching.

Seeking a fourth term, McNamara was defeated in the 2009 election by former Hervey Bay Mayor [[Ted Sorensen (politician)|Ted Sorensen]].

