{{Infobox Software |name = Australian Integrated Forecast System |logo = |screenshot = [[File:AIFS On Screen Analysis.jpg|200px]] [[File:K124G4Bvvk9zEx muQ8nlw204404.jpg|200px]] |caption = Screenshots of On Screen Analysis & 2D Radar Display |collapsible = |author = |developer = |released = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |latest release version = |latest release date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |latest preview version = |latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |programming language = |operating system = |platform = |size = |language = |status = |genre = |license = |website = }} The '''Australian Integrated Forecast System''' (AIFS) is a [[UNIX]] and [[Linux]] -based processing, display, analysis and communications system for [[Meteorology|meteorological]] data.
It incorporates facilities for the ingest and storage of meteorological and [[Hydrology|hydrological]] observations, which can be displayed, analysed and manipulated on screen. Tools are also provided for alerting, [[chart]] plotting and the preparation and dissemination of [[Weather forecast|forecasts]] and warnings to the public.<ref>http://ssu1.bom.gov.au/pub/ims/aifs.html{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
AIFS is currently running on [[AIX]], [[HP-UX]] and [[Linux]] platforms in [[Australia]], [[Fiji]], [[Indonesia]] and [[Malaysia]].
Development began in 1991 as a replacement for the Automated Regional Operations System (AROS), built on [[NonStop SQL|Tandem NonStop]] architecture.
